      <text>
        The mushroom paste sat heavy in Kira's stomach—not unpleasant, just _present_ — real food, actual nutrition. One more survival basic checked off — she sat in her quarters with Scout settled nearby and let herself think beyond the next crisis for the first time since the crash.

        Wound healing, food established, shelter functional, water available.

        She was alive — surviving and adapting to bureaucratic plant life through sheer stubborn determination and strategic phrasing. But she was also still stranded on an alien planet with no ship, no crew, no way home.

        Rescue seemed…

        _She thought of the_ _Meridian_ being attacked in deep space, far from trade routes. Even if someone noticed they were missing, finding her here — on an uncharted planet in the Outer Reaches — the math wasn't good.

        She said quietly, "Buddy — what's our realistic timeline for rescue?"
        —
        The system replied, "Based on last known position and standard search protocols — if rescue operations were initiated immediately upon our disappearance, search radius would take approximately six to eight months to reach this system — accounting for detection difficulties of uncharted planets, potential delays, and probability factors…"

        Kira said, "Just tell me."

        The system answered, "Twelve to eighteen months — minimum. If they search at all."

        There it was — a year; maybe more; maybe never.

        ¶

        She imagined living on mushroom paste and bureaucratic forms. Scout rolled closer, pressing against her leg — comfort or commiseration, both, probably.

        Kira asked toward the walls, "Is there anyone here who could help — with unusual situations? Someone with more… authority?"

        Holloway responded, fruiting body sprouting near the entrance — its warm, fluting voice considering before it spoke, "Authority for unusual situations? Most coordination happens through collective consensus — but for truly exceptional cases, we have Elder Heartwood."

        Kira sat up straighter and asked, "Elder Heartwood?"

        Holloway replied in the same voice, "Yes — the oldest among us. Very wise — handles complex situations that don't fit standard protocols."

        Something that didn't fit standard protocols — like a stranded human. Hope flared bright and desperate in Kira's chest.

        Kira asked, "Can I talk to them — to Elder Heartwood?"

        Holloway's fruiting bodies rustled, an uncertainty in the sound, then the voice said, "Ah — Elder Heartwood is… distant — geographically and temporally. They exist in slow time — growth cycles measured in seasons, thought processes taking days or weeks. Communication is challenging."

        The hope dimmed slightly. Kira asked, "But possible?"

        Holloway answered, "Yes — we can file a formal query through established channels. Elder Heartwood does respond to requests for guidance — eventually."

        Kira said, "How eventually?"

        Holloway replied, "Typical response time for standard queries: four to six weeks — for complex, exceptional cases like yours — perhaps two to three months."

        _Months_. Of course. Nothing here happened quickly.
      </text>
