      <text>
        But still — an actual authority, someone who handled exceptions and might understand "help this human get home" as a valid request beyond standard protocols.

        Kira said, "I want to file that query — whatever the formal process is."

        Holloway sounded genuinely pleased. "Wonderful! This is very appropriate use of exception-handling channels — I'll prepare the documentation immediately!"

        Forms — obviously there would be forms. Kira was learning to work within this system; she could do forms — she could wait months if it meant a chance.

        Over the next hour, Holloway guided her through the formal query process.

        Holloway listed the required fields:
        "Petitioner information — full name, arrival circumstances, current status."
        "Nature of exception — stranded non-plant lifeform requiring assistance beyond standard protocols."
        "Requested guidance — recommendations for long-term survival, potential contact with human civilization, any available transportation or communication resources."
        "Supporting documentation — medical records, crash site location, resource requirements, adaptation challenges."

        Buddy provided data. Kira provided context. Holloway documented everything with meticulous care.

        Scout watched the whole process, occasionally bouncing encouragingly.

        Holloway announced, "Query complete! I'll transmit this through the network to Elder Heartwood's grove — response timeline: estimated eight to twelve weeks, accounting for processing time and Elder Heartwood's deliberation pace."

        Eight to twelve weeks.
        ¶
        Two to three months of bureaucratic plant life — of morning wellness checks and dietary assessments — of mushroom paste meals and wound care documentation.

        Two to three months of waiting.

        But also — hope. Actual hope.

        Kira said, "Thank you — seriously, for filing this, for helping."

        Holloway replied warmly, "Of course! This is exactly the kind of exceptional situation Elder Heartwood exists to address — you should receive guidance eventually."

        «Eventually.»

        The word hung there — simultaneously reassuring and exhausting.

        Holloway continued warmly, "In the meantime — you're adapting remarkably well! Your progress with protocols has been excellent — we're very pleased with your integration."

        Integration, like she was joining their community instead of being stranded with no other options. But... wasn't she, though? Learning their language — working within their systems — building routines.

        Adapting.

        Kira said, "I'm trying."

        Holloway asked, "Now — shall we schedule your next wellness check for tomorrow morning?"

        Daily wellness checks. For months. Maybe years. This was her life now.

        But she'd filed the query — started the process — reached for the one authority who might actually help beyond forms and protocols. It wasn't giving up — it was strategic patience.

        Kira said, "Yes — schedule the wellness check."

        Scout bounced approvingly.

        Later, lying on the soft moss and woven plant fibers that served as bed, Kira stared at the bioluminescent ceiling and took stock.
      </text>
