      <text>
        Three days since the crash — three days since her entire world exploded.

        She'd survived impact, treated severe injury, met alien sentient plants who learned human language from H R manuals, navigated bureaucratic onboarding, established food sources through fungal chemistry, and filed formal exception queries with ancient tree authorities.

        Her life had become surreal, absurdist science fiction — and somehow she was managing it.

        Scout settled near the entrance — constant guardian, non-verbal companion, the little plant there for every crisis, every form, every exhausted moment.

        Kira said, softly into the dim light:
        "Thanks — for sticking with me."

        Scout bounced once — gentle, understanding.

        Kira said to the ceiling — to herself:
        "Two to three months — I can do two to three months — I've done three days; I can do more."

        Because what choice did she have? But also — because she could. She was learning the system, getting better at it, phrasing requests strategically, working with each plant's strengths, finding humor in the absurdity.

        Adapting. Surviving. And now, maybe — _maybe_ — finding a way out.

        Elder Heartwood — whoever they were, whatever wisdom they held.

        The query was filed — the wait had begun.

        ¶

        Kira closed her eyes.

        Tomorrow would bring more forms, more wellness checks, more mushroom-paste meals — but also another day survived, another day closer to answers, another day of strange, absurd, bureaucratic life on an alien planet.

        She could do this — had to do this — was doing this.

        One impossible adaptation at a time.
      </text>
